		<title>Using specific HTML5 input types on a login form</title>
		<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="https://rawgit.com/w3c/wcag/master/css/sources.css"/>
	</head>
<body>
		<h1>Using specific HTML5 input types on a login form</h1>
<section id="meta">
			<h2>Metadata</h2>
			<p id="id"></p>
			<p id="technology"></p>
			<p id="type"></p>
	</section>
	<section id="applicability">
		<h2>When to Use</h2>
		<p >This technique relates to:	<a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG21/#identify-input-purpose">Success	Criteria 1.3.5 (Identify Input Purpose)</a></p>
		<p >This technique can be used when the purpose of the form field can be determined from the HTML type element and the context of the page. The most common example of this is would be a login form where there are only two form fields,  username and password. The information entered is about the end user and the page title is something like &quot;Login&quot;.</p>
    </section>
	<section id="description">
	  <h2>Description</h2>
		
			<p>The objective of this technique is to provide the provide a programmatically determinable purpose for form fields that are collecting information about the user and are using the HTML <code>type</code> attribute. There are limited situations where this technique will work because the purpose of a field cannot often be determined by the <code>type</code> attribute. For instance,  <code>type="text"</code>, <code>type="radio"</code>, <code>type="checkbox"</code> attributes don't say much about the purpose of an input. However, if a page is a login screen and  <code>type="email"</code> and <code>type="password"</code> are on the two form fields, the purpose is clear from the context of the page and the <code>type</code> of form fields. Browser autocomplete features recognise <code>type="password"</code>.</p>
</section>
		<section id="examples">
			<h2>Examples</h2>
			
			<section class="example">
				<h3>Using <code>type="email"</code> and <code>type="password" </code></h3>
				<p>A login page has two form fields for a user's email  and password. </p>
				
				<code>
				<p>&lt;head&gt;<br>
				&lt;title&gt;Login to ACME application&lt;/title&gt;<br>
				...
				<br>
				&lt;/head&gt;				<br>
				</p>
		      <p>
		      &lt;h1&gt;Login&lt;/h1&gt;	</p>
		      <p>&lt;label for=&quot;username&quot;&gt;Your email address&lt;/label&gt; &lt;input id=&quot;username&quot; type=&quot;email&quot; ... &gt; <br>
	          &lt;label for=&quot;password&quot;&gt;Password&lt;/label&gt; &lt;input id=&quot;password&quot; type=&quot;password&quot; ... &gt;
	        </p>  </code>
			</section>
		</section>
		<section id="tests">
		  <h2>Tests</h2>
			<section class="test-procedure">
			  <h3>Procedure</h3>
				<ol>
					<li>Step 1: Examine the page title and heading to confirm it is about the user</li>
					<li>Step 2: Confirm that the <code>type </code>attribute on <code> &lt;input&gt;</code> element describes the purpose of the input (what is required of the user).</li>
				</ol>
			</section>
			<section class="test-results">
				<h3>Expected Results</h3>
				<ul>
					<li>If step one and two are true then the test passes and the technique is sufficient.</li>
				</ul>
			</section>
</section>
